{{Infobox language |name=Hakaona |nativename=Havakona |states=[[Angola]], [[Namibia]] |region= |ethnicity= |speakers=? |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=[[Kavango–Southwest]] |fam7=[[Southwest Bantu]] |iso3=none |glotto=none |guthrie=included in R.311 }}
'''Hakaona''' (Hakawona, Havakona) is a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]] of Angola and Namibia. Until perhaps Anita Pfouts (2003), it was considered a dialect of [[Herero language|Herero]].<ref>[http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/history/ehret/kinship/BantuClassification%204-09.pdf Bantu Classification] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624221430/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/history/ehret/kinship/BantuClassification%204-09.pdf |date=2012-06-24 }}, Ehret, 2009.</ref>
Maho (2009) sets up a Northwest Herero language, which includes [[Zemba language|Zimba]]; from the map, it would appear to include Himba and Hakaona as well.<ref name="Guthrie"/>
